{
  "intro": "Indirect object pronouns show who receives, benefits from, or is affected by an action. They often answer to whom or for whom.",
  "overview": {
    "body": "The main indirect object pronouns are me, te, le, nos, and les. They usually appear before the conjugated verb: me escribe, le doy, nos mandan.",
    "use_note": "indirect object pronouns"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "spanish": "Le escribo a Ana.",
      "english": "I write to Ana."
    },
    {
      "spanish": "Nos dieron la información.",
      "english": "They gave us the information."
    }
  ],
  "uses": [
    {
      "heading": "Communication and giving",
      "body": "Indirect objects are common with decir, escribir, mandar, dar, explicar, and contar.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "spanish": "Te mandé el archivo.",
          "english": "I sent you the file."
        },
        {
          "spanish": "Les expliqué la regla.",
          "english": "I explained the rule to them."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "heading": "Clarify le and les",
      "body": "Le and les can refer to different people, so Spanish often adds a + person for clarity.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "spanish": "Le escribí a mi jefe.",
          "english": "I wrote to my boss."
        },
        {
          "spanish": "Les di el número a mis padres.",
          "english": "I gave the number to my parents."
        }
      ]
    }
